Problem 5.2

The “yes” and “no” in the gray bars refer to whether or not the person is pregnant.

ggplot(NCHS) +
  aes(x = bmi, fill = stratum, colour = sex) +
  geom_density() +
  scale_fill_gradient() +
  scale_color_hue(direction = 1) +
  theme_light() +
  facet_wrap(vars(pregnant))

Your Turn: explore the diamonds data

Task: Produce an interesting graphic of the diamonds data set. The graphic should represent AT LEAST 3 variables. Write a few sentences to describe what you have learned. Remember that the esquisser() function will not work in a markdown document. You must create the plot using the console and then copy the expression into this assignment.

data("diamonds")

ggplot(diamonds) +
  aes(x = clarity, y = price, fill = color) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_hue(direction = 1) +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 5L)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(cut), scales = "free_x")

I have learned that there are a variety of different ways to represent data using the esquisser() function. With these many options, I have also learned that it is important to be extremely careful in choosing which variables to display because in a real-world situation, it may make a difference on how the data is interpreted. Regarding the diamond data set and how it was displayed, I learned that the price of a diamond is greatly affected by its cut and its clarity. I now know that ideal cut diamonds are the most expensive along with SI2, SI1, VS2, and VS1 clarity diamonds. finally, I learned that different diamonds used in this graphic have different price ranges. For example, diamond D was more expensive than diamond J in most instances. If this data were presented a different way, it may have been difficult to figure out the prices of these types of diamonds, but it may have been possible to discover different qualities of them, which is one of the many benefits of displaying data.
